DADA2_template

Kate Bowie

11/14/2019

  • Update: code re-run and updated 10/07/2020
  • Purpose:
  • Load workspace from DADA2_setup
  • Trims and filter the forward and reverse reads.
  • Determine the error rates in our reads using our error DADA2 wrapper function
  • combine all identical sequences into unique sequences
    • Invoke our sample inference DADA2 wrapper
    • Merge the forward and reverse reads together to obtain the full denoised sequences.
    • Construct the asv sequence table.
    • Remove any chimeras present.
    • Track what reads made it through filtering.
  • quick save workspace to troubleshoot
    • Assign taxonomy.
    • Make mapping file sample names agree with seqtab.nochim
    • Create Phyloseq Object.
    • Save the R workspace containing all the read data and intermediate steps.
  • Clean up workspace and remove all environment variables but the phyloseq object.

Update: code re-run and updated 10/07/2020

Updated the silva taxonomic database to 138. Updated paths from putting this all on box. Updated reverse and foward trimming from 0 to 20.

Purpose:

This template serves as a starting point for processing 16S rRNA gene sequencing data with DADA2. This template should be used to keep track of how the 16S rRNA gene sequencing data was processed.

To get started, make a copy of this template.

Load workspace from DADA2_setup

Next, load the workspace XXX_DADA2_setup.RData that was created by running DADA2_setup.Rmd.

# define workspace name
DADA2_setup_workspace <- "623_DADA2_setup.RData"
# load the workspace
load(DADA2_setup_workspace)

# source our list Functions
source("DADA2_Functions.R")
## Loading required package: Rcpp
## Warning: package 'Rcpp' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Warning: replacing previous import 'vctrs::data_frame' by 'tibble::data_frame'
## when loading 'dplyr'
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.6.2

Trims and filter the forward and reverse reads.

Input your decided upon parameters for trimming and filtering the raw .fastq files for each sample in your sequencing run. You will know which parameters to choose after careful inspection of the DADA2_setup.html knitted output, which contains graphs showing the quality profile of the forward and reverse reads for a subset of samples.

forward_trim <- 20 
reverse_trim <- 20 
forward_trunc <- 240
reverse_trunc <- 230 

filtered_F_R_reads_list <- filter(read_path,write_path,fnFs, fnRs, sample.names, forward_trim, reverse_trim, forward_trunc, reverse_trunc)

filtFs <- filtered_F_R_reads_list$forw
filtRs <- filtered_F_R_reads_list$rev

Determine the error rates in our reads using our error DADA2 wrapper function

# invoke our error function
errorlist <- error(filtFs, filtRs)
## Warning in learnErrors(filtFs, nreads = 1e+06, randomize = TRUE): The nreads
## parameter is DEPRECATED. Please update your code with the nbases parameter.
## 236109720 total bases in 1073226 reads from 4 samples will be used for learning the error rates.
## Warning in learnErrors(filtRs, nreads = 1e+06, randomize = TRUE): The nreads
## parameter is DEPRECATED. Please update your code with the nbases parameter.
## 221723670 total bases in 1055827 reads from 4 samples will be used for learning the error rates.
# extract the estimated errors for the forward and reverse reads
errF <- errorlist$forw
errR <- errorlist$rev

# plot inline here
plotErrors(errF)
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

plotErrors(errR)
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

combine all identical sequences into unique sequences

dereplist <- dereplicate(filtFs, filtRs,sample.names)
